**Encryption is under attack.**

French law enforcement now has the power to snoop by remotely controlling
unsuspecting people’s electronic devices. It’s not clear how they plan to
execute this. Perhaps they
[already](https://www.tomsguide.com/us/nsa-remotely-turn-on-phones,news-18854.html)
have? Of course, the Justice Minister has been adamant that this is
[nothing](https://www.lemonde.fr/en/france/article/2023/07/06/france-set-to-allow-police-to-spy-through-phones_6044269_7.html)
like the surveillance society that Orwell described in 1984. And of course, the
lawmakers were quick to exempt themselves from the invasive law.

The French authorities aren't alone in wanting backdoors in digital devices. On
the other side of the English Channel, lawmakers in the United Kingdom are
about to mandate backdoors in all end-to-end encrypted messaging systems. The
proposed [Online Safety
Bill](https://bills.parliament.uk/bills/3137/publications) mandates private
messaging services to monitor the messages of users. This perpetual wiretap
will, allegedly, make the United Kingdom “[the safest place in the world to be
online while defending free
expression](https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/online-safety-bill-supporting-documents)”.
Similar moves are underway in
[Spain](https://www.wired.com/story/europe-break-encryption-leaked-document-csa-law/)
and the [United States of America](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/EARN_IT_Act).

Back in France, digital surveillance of dissenting socio-political movements
had been intensifying for years now. Comrades in environmental groups
(https://lessoulevementsdelaterre.org/blog/un-traceur-gps-retrouve-sous-le-vehicule-du-porte-parolede-bassines-non-merci),
or just at an anarchist library
(https://bibliothequelibertad.noblogs.org/post/2022/04/02/un-micro-trouve-a-la-bibliotheque-anarchiste-libertad/)
are being surveilled with military-grade equipment. As if that wasn’t enough,
the mere use of privacy-preserving tools like Tails and Tor is being treated as
evidence of criminal behaviour to muzzle dissenting political groups. In the
French senate, the Minister of Interior
[desired](https://www.laquadrature.net/en/2023/06/05/criminalization-of-encryption-the-8-december-case/)
the power to hack into the phones of environmental activists using Signal,
WhatsApp, or Telegram. In the “8 December” case, the suspects’ use of Tails,
and apparent distrust of GAFAM was used to support an already nebulous case.

In 2009, we created Tails exactly this context: so that activists wouldn't get
in troubles merely because of how they used computers.

In 2023, not much has changed. It’s saddening and enraging that digital privacy
and safety are rapidly getting out of reach. Tails’s mission as important now,
if not more, as it was 15 years ago.

